LAST UPDATES

Use of AI: Placebo Effect Increases Risk-Taking

A recent study by the Chair of Human-Centered Ubiquitous Media led by Prof. Dr. Albrecht Schmidt has revealed that users who believe that AI is enhancing their cognitive abilities tend to increase their risk-taking behavior, regardless of whether the AI is actually assisting them or not. The study suggests that the hype around AI applications affects the expectations of users and can lead to riskier behaviour. The researchers recommend assessing the actual benefit of AI applications before releasing them and involving users more in the development process.

Read more here

Stable Diffusion takes the World

Stable Diffusion, the text-to-image deep learning model developed by LMU’s Computer Vision & Learning together with the start-up Stability AI, has become wildly popular and has been adopted and extended in various ways. Its development has been reported on by various news outlets including Die Zeit, Süddeutsche Zeitung and TechCrunch.

Women in Data Science Munich

Registration is now open for the Women in Data Science (WiDS) Munich Conference, an independent event organized by LMU, TUM, BERD@NFDI, MDSI, SIXT SE,  and TUM Think Tank to coincide with the annual Global Women in Data Science Conference held at Stanford University and an estimated 150+ locations worldwide. All genders are invited to attend WiDS regional events, which features outstanding women doing outstanding work.

Munich AI Lecture with Prof. Dr. Giles Hooker

The Munich AI Lectures series continues with a talk by Prof. Dr. Giles Hooker. On  1st June at 16:00, he will give a talk on "V-Statistics and Variance Estimation: Inference for Random Forests and Other Ensembles". Hooker is a professor in the Department of Statistics at UC Berkeley. His research interests focus on the interface of statistics with both machine learning and applied mathematics, as well as functional data analysis and robust statistics. Much of his research has been inspired by applications in ecology and healthcare. The talk will be live-streamed online.
